Main Experimental Results\n556\t\n557\tThe results obtained on the evaluation datasets are summarized in Table II. The baseline model achieves performance comparable to that reported in [23], evaluated using the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve, and the Equal Error Rate (EER). Performance is also quantified using the Area Under the Curve (AUC).\n558\tThe results of the three continual learning strategies introduced in II-C are illustrated in Fig.3.\n559\tIt can be observed that full retraining performs very well on the target dataset (average EER on new dataset), but results in a dramatic loss of accuracy on the source dataset ASVspoof 2019 ( AUC and EER on average). The largest loss is reasonably observed on ADD since the language change from English to Chinese. Performing a partial update (domain adaptation) proved to be more robust, as the average AUC decrease is on the target domain, but the loss on the source domain is AUC and EER increases by on average. It is also worth noting that only a small number of parameters must be retrained (see Table III), making it very efficient.\n560\tThe domain translation strategy represents a good trade-off between classification performances and computational complexity\n561\tsince the average AUC loss on target domains is , but we preserve the accuracy on the source domain ( AUC, EER) while updating only a limited number of parameters.\n562\t\n563\tThe experimental results also show that the proposed approaches can be applied to cross-lingual adaptation, since ADD dataset includes Chinese language speech samples. The traceback translation model proves to be capable of handling datasets in different languages while keeping the same classification accuracy.\n564\t\n565\tIV-C Ablation studies\n566\t\n567\tTo determine the impact of diffusion-based data augmentation on model performance, we trained the baseline model on only the ASVspoof 2019 training set, and then we included both original and generated samples. Experimental results show consistent performance gains with data augmentation: classification accuracy increased from to , while the AUC improved from to .\n568\t\n569\tMoreover, we enabled/disabled the different components in (6) and evaluated their impact on the final accuracy. With only (Prototype-Consistency), EER for FoR/ITW/ADD increases to , , respectively, while using only (CORAL loss), the respective EER is , , , showing that their combination is, on average, more effective on all the datasets.\n570\t\n571\tV Conclusions\n572\t\n573\tIn this paper, we investigated the effectiveness of multiple continual learning techniques for audio deepfake detection to mitigate the problem of catastrophic forgetting.\n574\t\n575\tOur experiments showed that all the approaches achieve good detection performance, but the full retraining and domain adaptation methods are not able to retain previously learned knowledge.\n576\tWe proposed a novel approach based on domain translation that achieves high detection rates without requiring the retraining of the backbone architecture and, at the same time, preserves the detection accuracy on the original dataset.\n577\t\n578\tFuture work will focus on extending the evaluation to a larger number of datasets to test scalability and robustness against different types of domain shifts. Additionally, exploring different model architectures could further improve performance in cross-domain and cross-lingual audio deepfake detection.\n579\t\n580\tAcknowledgment\n581\t\n582\tThe authors would like to thank Davide Salvi, Viola Negroni, Luca Bondi, Paolo Bestagini, and Stefano Tubaro of Politecnico di Milano for their support in the experimental comparison with [23].\n583\t\n584\tReferences\n585\t\n586\t[1]\n587\tZ. Ba, Q. Wen, P. Cheng, Y. Wang, F. Lin, L. Lu, and Z. Liu (2023)\n588\t\n589\tTransferring audio deepfake detection capability across languages.\n590\t\n591\tIn Proceedings of the ACM Web Conference 2023,\n592\t\n593\tWWW ’23, New York, NY, USA, pp. 2033–2044.\n594\t\n595\tExternal Links: ISBN 9781450394161,\n596\tLink,\n597\tDocument\n598\t\n599\tCited by: §I.\n600\t\n601\t[2]\n602\tK. Bhagtani, A. K. S. Yadav, P. Bestagini, and E. J. Delp (2024)\n603\t\n604\tAre recent deepfake speech generators detectable?.\n605\t\n606\tIn Proceedings of the 2024 ACM Workshop on Information Hiding and Multimedia Security,\n607\t\n608\tIH&MMSec ’24, New York, NY, USA, pp. 277–282.\n609\t\n610\tExternal Links: ISBN 9798400706370,\n611\tLink,\n612\tDocument\n613\t\n614\tCited by: §I.\n615\t\n616\t[3]\n617\tX. Chen, W. Lu, R. Zhang, J. Xu, X. Lu, L. Zhang, and J. Wei (2025)\n618\t\n619\tContinual unsupervised domain adaptation for audio deepfake detection.\n620\t\n621\tIn 2025 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP),\n622\t\n623\tVol. , Hyderabad, India, pp. 1–5.\n624\t\n625\tExternal Links: Document\n626\t\n627\tCited by: §I.\n628\t\n629\t[4]\n630\tF. Dong, Q. Tang, Y. Bai, and Z. Wang (2024)\n631\t\n632\tAdvancing continual learning for robust deepfake audio classification.\n633\t\n634\tIn TENCON 2024 - 2024 IEEE Region 10 Conference (TENCON),\n635\t\n636\tVol. , Singapore, pp. 302–305.\n637\t\n638\tExternal Links: Document\n639\t\n640\tCited by: §I.\n641\t\n642\t[5]\n643\tS. V. Eeckt and H. Van Hamme (2023)\n644\t\n645\tUsing adapters to overcome catastrophic forgetting in end-to-end automatic speech recognition.\n646\t\n647\tIn 2023 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP),\n648\t\n649\tVol. , pp. 1–5.\n650\t\n651\tExternal Links: Document\n652\t\n653\tCited by: §II-C3.\n654\t\n655\t[6]\n656\tY. Gong, Y. Chung, and J. Glass (2021)\n657\t\n658\tAST: Audio Spectrogram Transformer.\n659\t\n660\tIn Interspeech 2021,\n661\t\n662\t pp. 571–575.\n663\t\n664\tExternal Links: Document,\n665\tISSN 2958-1796\n666\t\n667\tCited by: §IV-A,\n668\tTABLE I.\n669\t\n670\t[7]\n671\tK. He, X. Zhang, S. Ren, and J. Sun (2016-06)\n672\t\n673\tDeep residual learning for image recognition.\n674\t\n675\tIn Proceedings of the IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (CVPR),\n676\t\n677\tLas Vegas, NV, USA, pp. .\n678\t\n679\tCited by: §II-B,\n680\tTABLE I,\n681\tTABLE I.\n682\t\n683\t[8]\n684\tN. Houlsby, A. Giurgiu, S. Jastrzebski, B. Morrone, Q. De Laroussilhe, A. Gesmundo, M. Attariyan, and S. Gelly (2019-09–15 Jun)\n685\t\n686\tParameter-efficient transfer learning for NLP.\n687\t\n688\tIn Proceedings of the 36th International Conference on Machine Learning, K. Chaudhuri and R. Salakhutdinov (Eds.),\n689\t\n690\tProceedings of Machine Learning Research, Vol. 97, pp. 2790–2799.\n691\t\n692\tExternal Links: Link\n693\t\n694\tCited by: §II-C3.\n695\t\n696\t[9]\n697\tA. Howard, M. Sandler, G. Chu, L. Chen, B. Chen, M. Tan, W. Wang, Y. Zhu, R. Pang, V. Vasudevan, Q. V. Le, and H. Adam (2019-10)\n698\t\n699\tSearching for mobilenetv3.\n700\t\n701\tIn Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF International Conference on Computer Vision (ICCV),\n702\t\n703\tCited by: §IV-A,\n704\tTABLE I.\n705\t\n706\t[10]\n707\tHugging Face API models\n708\t\n709\tUNet2DModel.\n710\t\n711\tNote: Accessed on 2025-09-10\n712\t\n713\tExternal Links: Link\n714\t\n715\tCited by: §II-A.\n716\t\n717\t[11]\n718\tS. Kessler, B. Thomas, and S. Karout (2022)\n719\t\n720\tAn adapter based pre-training for efficient and scalable self-supervised speech representation learning.\n721\t\n722\tIn 2022 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP),\n723\t\n724\tVol. , pp. 3179–3183.\n725\t\n726\tExternal Links: Document\n727\t\n728\tCited by: §II-C3.\n729\t\n730\t[12]\n731\tM. Li, Y. Ahmadiadli, and X.-P. Zhang (2025-02)\n732\t\n733\tA survey on speech deepfake detection.\n734\t\n735\tACM Comput. Surv. 57 (7).\n736\t\n737\tExternal Links: ISSN 0360-0300,\n738\tLink,\n739\tDocument\n740\t\n741\tCited by: §I.\n742\t\n743\t[13]\n744\tZ. Liu, H. Mao, C. Wu, C. Feichtenhofer, T. Darrell, and S. Xie (2022-06)\n745\t\